how much he loved me or something.

324
00:32:38,081 --> 00:32:40,374
NED:
How did he get so fat?

325
00:32:40,541 --> 00:32:43,919
MATTY:
Stock market, real estate, investments.

326
00:32:44,087 --> 00:32:46,713
He doesn't tell me much,
but I've picked up a little.

327
00:32:46,881 --> 00:32:50,217
- I know they own a lot of land
along shore. - Who's "they"?

328
00:32:50,385 --> 00:32:54,262
MATTY: He's never introduced me to anyone.
I'm not sure if they're all legitimate.

329
00:32:55,306 --> 00:32:58,225
NED: I wonder what they call themselves.
Maybe I've heard of them.

330
00:32:58,393 --> 00:33:02,270
MATTY: I know they own that old place
near Miranda Beach, The Breakers.

331
00:33:02,438 --> 00:33:05,482
The Breakers? I thought Morrie Fisher
owned that land.

332
00:33:05,650 --> 00:33:07,693
Edmund mentioned it once.

333
00:33:08,194 --> 00:33:10,737
Ned, it scares me
to talk about these things.

334
00:33:10,905 --> 00:33:11,947
Why?

335
00:33:12,115 --> 00:33:14,408
- You know.
- No, I don't.

336
00:33:14,575 --> 00:33:17,536
Let's just not.
Let's just not think about all he's got.

337
00:33:17,704 --> 00:33:19,454
Wait a minute.

338
00:33:20,581 --> 00:33:23,667
Tell me exactly what it is
that frightens you.

339
00:33:25,211 --> 00:33:27,337
I'm afraid because...

340
00:33:28,548 --> 00:33:30,340
...when I think about it...

341
00:33:30,508 --> 00:33:32,467
...I wish he'd die.

342
00:33:33,219 --> 00:33:37,556
That's really what I want.
It's horrible and it's ugly...

343
00:33:37,724 --> 00:33:39,891
...and it's what I most want.

344
00:33:41,728 --> 00:33:44,438
- That's where we're at, isn't it?
- What do you mean?

345
00:33:44,605 --> 00:33:46,940
That's what we're thinking.
How good it would be...

346
00:33:47,108 --> 00:33:49,192
...if he was gone.
It would be real sweet.

347
00:33:49,360 --> 00:33:52,029
No, Ned, please. Don't.
Don't talk about it.

348
00:33:52,196 --> 00:33:54,239
Talk is dangerous,
it makes things happen.

349
00:33:54,407 --> 00:33:56,658
- It makes them real.
- Don't let it scare you.

350
00:33:56,826 --> 00:33:58,827
Because he's not gonna die.

351
00:33:58,995 --> 00:34:02,497
Nothing wrong with him, is there?
No reason to think he's gonna die?

352
00:34:02,665 --> 00:34:03,957
- No.
- That's right.

353
00:34:04,125 --> 00:34:06,460
So we might as well forget about it.

354
00:34:06,919 --> 00:34:10,047
It's not gonna just happen
to make things nice for us.

355
00:34:11,132 --> 00:34:13,091
It won't just happen.

356
00:34:41,037 --> 00:34:43,038
NED: If you leave him,
you'll come out all right.

357
00:34:43,206 --> 00:34:45,624
- Of a divorce?
- Yeah, he's ripe.

358
00:34:45,792 --> 00:34:49,086
No. I signed a prenuptial agreement.

359
00:34:50,004 --> 00:34:52,506
- What?
- He insisted.

360
00:34:52,673 --> 00:34:54,174
He blamed it on his sister Roz.

361
00:34:54,342 --> 00:34:57,511
She's always hated me,
but I know he wanted it too.

362
00:34:57,678 --> 00:35:00,347
- How is it?
- It's bad.

363
00:35:00,515 --> 00:35:03,850
I get some money for a year,
not much. That's it.

364
00:35:06,437 --> 00:35:10,524
Does it matter, Ned?
Tell me the truth, please.

365
00:35:11,734 --> 00:35:16,363
The truth.
I had wished you were gonna be loaded.

366
00:35:18,991 --> 00:35:20,283
Does it matter? No.

367
00:35:20,785 --> 00:35:22,202
No.

368
00:35:28,459 --> 00:35:30,877
God, you make me happy.

369
00:35:35,216 --> 00:35:37,425
It's time for your present.

370
00:35:46,352 --> 00:35:50,689
From now on, when it starts coming
down on you, I'll be there to protect you.

371
00:35:55,736 --> 00:35:57,112
[NED CHUCKLES]

372
00:35:57,280 --> 00:35:59,906
Try it on.
I bet I guessed the size right.

373
00:36:06,497 --> 00:36:07,581
I love it.

374
00:36:08,291 --> 00:36:10,417
- I wanna see.
- Here.

375
00:36:33,482 --> 00:36:35,108
Hello, sweetheart.

376
00:36:35,276 --> 00:36:37,903
Have I got a nice present for you.

377
00:36:38,863 --> 00:36:40,655
Hi, Aunt Matty.

378
00:36:41,616 --> 00:36:43,116
Heather.

379
00:36:44,535 --> 00:36:46,494
- What is it again? What?
- Rover.

380
00:36:46,662 --> 00:36:50,415
- It's between first and second.
- Rover. That's not a shortstop?

381
00:36:50,583 --> 00:36:53,460
No. The shortstop
is between second and third.

382
00:36:53,628 --> 00:36:55,503
Oh, good, that's the way I remember it.

383
00:36:55,880 --> 00:36:57,839
You have a good time.

384
00:36:59,342 --> 00:37:02,636
You don't really mind, do you?
Roz will pick her up Thursday.

385
00:37:03,512 --> 00:37:06,139
Don't worry.
Roz won't stay overnight.

386
00:37:06,849 --> 00:37:09,059
She can do whatever she wants.

387
00:37:49,767 --> 00:37:52,686
Oh, my God. You scared me.

388
00:37:54,480 --> 00:37:56,648
You shouldn't be here.
Heather's upstairs.

389
00:37:56,816 --> 00:37:58,984
Asleep. And I know what I want.

390
00:37:59,193 --> 00:38:03,571
I know. I know. I missed you so badly,
but it's too dangerous.

391
00:38:03,739 --> 00:38:05,907
- She won't wake up now.
- Oh, you're so wet.

392
00:38:06,075 --> 00:38:08,451
I've been waiting out there
for two hours.

393
00:38:08,619 --> 00:38:10,704
You're so salty.

394
00:38:13,040 --> 00:38:14,582
Let me.

395
00:38:16,836 --> 00:38:18,044
Lie back.

396
00:38:18,212 --> 00:38:19,713
HEATHER:
Aunt Matty?

397
00:38:28,889 --> 00:38:29,889
What do you say?

398
00:38:30,057 --> 00:38:32,142
- I did.
- She did.

399
00:38:32,310 --> 00:38:34,394
Thank you, Aunt Matty.

400
00:38:34,562 --> 00:38:38,815
- Thanks, Matty. We appreciate it.
- A pleasure, Roz. Anytime.

401
00:39:12,183 --> 00:39:14,434
- Hi, Ned.
- It's just me tonight, Filomena.

402
00:39:14,602 --> 00:39:16,853
- Okay. Just one minute. All right?
- Yeah.

403
00:39:19,148 --> 00:39:20,523
Well, hello to you.

404
00:39:21,525 --> 00:39:27,864
Hello. Darling, this is Mr. Racine.
I'm sorry, I don't know your first name.

405
00:39:28,157 --> 00:39:29,324
Ned.

406
00:39:30,117 --> 00:39:31,618
Edmund Walker. Nice to meet you.

407
00:39:32,912 --> 00:39:35,205
Mr. Racine is the lawyer
I told you about.

408
00:39:35,373 --> 00:39:38,833
You remember, darling. He had a client
who wanted to buy the house.

409
00:39:39,001 --> 00:39:40,794
- I told him we weren't selling.
- Right.

410
00:39:41,003 --> 00:39:43,213
NED:
That hasn't changed, has it?

411
00:39:43,381 --> 00:39:45,131
No. No, we're very happy with it.

412
00:39:45,883 --> 00:39:48,385
I can understand that.
It's a terrific place.

413
00:39:49,720 --> 00:39:52,680
- Are you going in?
- I was gonna grab a bite, yeah.

414
00:39:53,557 --> 00:39:54,974
Well, join us.

415
00:39:55,142 --> 00:39:58,561
- No. Thanks, I don't want to interfere.
- No. Don't be silly. No.

416
00:39:58,771 --> 00:40:01,189
We have room for three, don't we?

417
00:40:01,357 --> 00:40:04,067
This place is great,
but you can't get near it on weekends.

418
00:40:04,235 --> 00:40:07,278
- I don't get down during the week much.
NED: Is that right?

419
00:40:09,573 --> 00:40:12,867
I was a lawyer.
I still am, I guess, but I don't practice.

420
00:40:13,077 --> 00:40:16,162
- I went to Columbia. And you?
NED: F.S.U.

421
00:40:16,330 --> 00:40:20,083
EDMUND: A good school.
I got bored with it quick.

422
00:40:20,251 --> 00:40:22,335
I guess I didn't have
the temperament for it.

423
00:40:22,878 --> 00:40:25,422
I wanted to make the money faster.

424
00:40:25,589 --> 00:40:26,923
Is there a living in it here?

425
00:40:27,591 --> 00:40:30,635
I can afford to send out my shirts...

426
00:40:30,803 --> 00:40:34,848
...and eat here once a month
if I don't order an appetizer.

427
00:40:36,183 --> 00:40:39,519
Yeah. Yeah, I figured that honest lawyers
didn't make very much...

428
00:40:39,687 --> 00:40:41,855
...and the other kind
were too slimy for me.

429
00:40:42,022 --> 00:40:44,816
Now, I'd rather be up-front
about shafting somebody.

430
00:40:44,984 --> 00:40:46,025
MATTY:
Edmund, really.

431
00:40:46,193 --> 00:40:48,570
- It's Mr. Racine's profession.
- That's all right.

432
00:40:48,779 --> 00:40:50,238
I don't like it much.

433
00:40:50,406 --> 00:40:52,615
Call me Ned, will you?

434
00:40:53,284 --> 00:40:55,034
EDMUND:
What's to like?

435
00:40:55,202 --> 00:40:58,288
That's the way of the world.
Most people despise their jobs.

436
00:40:58,539 --> 00:40:59,873
Do you?

437
00:41:00,374 --> 00:41:01,749
EDMUND:
No.

438
00:41:02,168 --> 00:41:03,418
No, I love it.

439
00:41:04,211 --> 00:41:06,045
But it's not a job.

440
00:41:06,380 --> 00:41:08,548
What is it exactly?

441
00:41:10,926 --> 00:41:13,636
Well, various things. This and that.

442
00:41:13,804 --> 00:41:16,431
- Here and there.
NED: You don't have to be specific.

443
00:41:19,143 --> 00:41:22,145
Finance, basically. Venture capital...

444
00:41:22,313 --> 00:41:24,731
...real estate investments.
We're into a few things.

445
00:41:25,399 --> 00:41:27,108
- Around here?
EDMUND: Some.

446
00:41:27,485 --> 00:41:31,237
- We own some things here.
- Edmund's company owns The Breakers.

447
00:41:31,864 --> 00:41:34,908
- Really?
EDMUND: It's not that simple, really.

448
00:41:35,117 --> 00:41:37,911
We have an interest
in a few places along the shore.

449
00:41:38,120 --> 00:41:40,914
For the land, someday.

450
00:41:41,081 --> 00:41:43,082
Don't try explaining that to her.

451
00:41:43,751 --> 00:41:46,711
I'm too dumb. A woman, you know.

452
00:41:47,630 --> 00:41:50,256
Well, I'll be right back.

453
00:41:50,799 --> 00:41:55,678
Then maybe we can talk about pantyhose
or something interesting.

454
00:42:02,228 --> 00:42:04,103
She's something, isn't she?

455
00:42:04,271 --> 00:42:06,189
- She is a lovely lady.
- Yeah.

456
00:42:06,357 --> 00:42:08,024
Yes, she is.

457
00:42:08,234 --> 00:42:10,443
And I'm crazy about her.

458
00:42:11,445 --> 00:42:13,446
If I thought she was seeing
another guy...

459
00:42:13,614 --> 00:42:15,615
I don't know.

460
00:42:15,950 --> 00:42:18,952
I could understand how it could happen,
her being the way she is.

461
00:42:19,119 --> 00:42:20,787
I could understand it...

462
00:42:21,789 --> 00:42:25,124
...but I think I'd kill the guy
with my bare hands.

463
00:42:25,584 --> 00:42:27,585
That's understanding.

464
00:42:27,753 --> 00:42:29,796
[BOTH LAUGHING]

465
00:42:31,549 --> 00:42:32,882
Please.

466
00:42:33,259 --> 00:42:36,844
You'd never believe
the dorkus she was with when I met her.

467
00:42:37,471 --> 00:42:40,848
The guy came to us
with a business proposition.

468
00:42:41,642 --> 00:42:44,227
We're always looking for opportunities.

469
00:42:44,395 --> 00:42:46,479
We're willing to take
an occasional risk...

470
00:42:46,647 --> 00:42:49,816
...if the downside isn't too steep,
if the conditions are right.

471
00:42:49,984 --> 00:42:53,486
But this guy,
he hadn't done his homework.

472
00:42:53,654 --> 00:42:57,448
He didn't know the bottom line.
That's how I knew he was full of shit.

473
00:42:57,658 --> 00:43:01,160
Gotta know the bottom line.
That's all that counts.

474
00:43:01,328 --> 00:43:03,871
But he didn't have the goods, this guy.

475
00:43:05,082 --> 00:43:06,833
He's like a lot of guys you run into.

476
00:43:07,001 --> 00:43:09,002
They wanna get rich,
they wanna do it quick.

477
00:43:09,169 --> 00:43:11,337
They wanna be there with one score.

478
00:43:11,505 --> 00:43:15,425
But they're not willing to do
what's necessary. You know what I mean?

479
00:43:15,593 --> 00:43:19,304
I'm not sure.
You mean, do the groundwork? Earn it?

480
00:43:19,513 --> 00:43:23,474
No. No, I mean, do what's necessary.

481
00:43:24,184 --> 00:43:26,477
Whatever is necessary.

482
00:43:28,522 --> 00:43:30,148
NED:
Yeah.

483
00:43:30,316 --> 00:43:35,069
I know that kind of guy.
I hate that. It makes me sick.

484
00:43:36,155 --> 00:43:37,196
Me too.

485
00:43:37,489 --> 00:43:39,532
I'm a lot like that.

486
00:44:14,902 --> 00:44:17,987
Some messages are on your desk.
I'll be back in an hour.

487
00:44:40,594 --> 00:44:42,095
Jesus. Did Beverly see you?

488
00:44:42,930 --> 00:44:44,681
I waited until I saw her leave.

489
00:44:45,683 --> 00:44:47,684
Please, don't be angry.

490
00:44:48,936 --> 00:44:51,270
Angry? I'm not angry.
How did you get in?

491
00:44:51,438 --> 00:44:53,147
MATTY:
It didn't lock.

492
00:44:54,608 --> 00:44:56,150
Ned, hold me.

493
00:44:57,277 --> 00:44:58,277
Please.

494
00:44:59,113 --> 00:45:01,030
Just hold me.

495
00:45:02,241 --> 00:45:04,617
Oh, God, I love you.

496
00:45:06,537 --> 00:45:08,037
He left this morning.

497
00:45:08,205 --> 00:45:10,289
I had to see you.

498
00:45:15,629 --> 00:45:16,838
I couldn't call.

499
00:45:17,005 --> 00:45:19,799
I was afraid to. I was afraid
you wouldn't let me come.

500
00:45:19,967 --> 00:45:22,135
That's right.
You mustn't call. Never call.

501
00:45:22,302 --> 00:45:24,846
Be very careful.
The phone company keeps records.

502
00:45:25,013 --> 00:45:26,889
I am careful.

503
00:45:27,057 --> 00:45:28,433
Ned, I hated it.

504
00:45:28,600 --> 00:45:31,644
I hated sitting there with the two of you.
I thought I'd scream.

505
00:45:31,812 --> 00:45:33,646
You called my apartment from the house.

506
00:45:33,814 --> 00:45:35,690
- No, never.
- Those two times?

507
00:45:35,858 --> 00:45:37,650
MATTY:
I went to phone booths.

508
00:45:37,818 --> 00:45:38,901
I'm afraid of him...

509
00:45:39,069 --> 00:45:43,156
That's good. Be very careful now
about the phones.

510
00:45:43,323 --> 00:45:46,075
- Why do you say this now?
- We can account for some calls.

511
00:45:46,243 --> 00:45:48,119
We've had some contact.
It'd make sense.

512
00:45:48,287 --> 00:45:50,496
Why, Ned? What's happened?

513
00:45:53,333 --> 00:45:55,376
Because we're gonna kill him.

514
00:45:58,130 --> 00:46:00,673
We both know that.

515
00:46:02,426 --> 00:46:04,510
It's what you want, isn't it?

516
00:46:05,345 --> 00:46:07,346
We knew it was coming.

517
00:46:07,514 --> 00:46:10,057
It's the only way we can have
everything we want.

518
00:46:26,742 --> 00:46:29,035
That man is going to die...

519
00:46:30,037 --> 00:46:33,790
...for no reason but we want him dead.

520
00:46:36,210 --> 00:46:38,920
He doesn't deserve it.
Let's not ever say that.

521
00:46:40,422 --> 00:46:41,464
We're doing it for us.

522
00:46:41,632 --> 00:46:45,468
You'll inherit half of everything he owns.
That's what the will says, right?

523
00:46:49,056 --> 00:46:50,890
That's it, then.

524
00:46:51,058 --> 00:46:52,642
That's it.

525
00:46:54,561 --> 00:46:56,479
We're gonna kill him.

526
00:46:56,897 --> 00:46:58,815
And I think I know how.

527
00:46:58,982 --> 00:47:01,692
- It's real, then?
- It's real, all right.

528
00:47:05,948 --> 00:47:09,659
And if we're not careful,
it's gonna be the last real thing we do.

529
00:48:31,199 --> 00:48:34,952
Her mother works plenty hard
to keep Heather on Edmund's mind.

530
00:48:35,120 --> 00:48:36,662
Always bringing her around...

531
00:48:36,830 --> 00:48:39,832
...always reporting
on everything she does in school.

532
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:42,335
That Roz is a smart one.

533
00:48:42,502 --> 00:48:46,672
And, you know, anything Heather inherits
goes to Roz. Heather won't even get a look.

534
00:48:46,840 --> 00:48:50,927
That's the part I can't stand, what seems
so wrong, that half of it should go to her.

535
00:48:51,094 --> 00:48:53,721
That's the way it is.
There's nothing we can do about it.

536
00:48:53,889 --> 00:48:55,473
Are you sure?

537
00:48:55,641 --> 00:48:59,060
I was thinking that maybe there is.

538
00:48:59,311 --> 00:49:03,022
The will is with Edmund's lawyer
in Miami. I know that.

539
00:49:04,399 --> 00:49:06,901
What if I could get him to bring it home?

540
00:49:07,069 --> 00:49:10,738
And couldn't we rewrite it? Change it?

541
00:49:11,615 --> 00:49:14,700
Every little change
would mean a lot for us, Ned.

542
00:49:15,410 --> 00:49:17,703
And you're a lawyer.
You know how to write it.

543
00:49:17,871 --> 00:49:19,330
It wouldn't seem so odd.

544
00:49:19,498 --> 00:49:24,543
I could say that he brought it home and
we decided to make some changes up here.

545
00:49:24,711 --> 00:49:27,129
- And I knew you already...
- No.

546
00:49:27,297 --> 00:49:28,381
Forget it.

547
00:49:28,548 --> 00:49:30,883
- I don't see why Heather should take half.
- Listen.

548
00:49:31,969 --> 00:49:34,595
Nothing strange can happen
in his life now.

549
00:49:34,763 --> 00:49:37,890
Not one thing out of the ordinary.

550
00:49:38,266 --> 00:49:40,101
That's vital, the most important thing.

551
00:49:40,268 --> 00:49:43,646
If it does,
the chances double that we get caught.

552
00:49:44,648 --> 00:49:46,065
You'll get half of everything.

553
00:49:46,233 --> 00:49:49,287
It'll be plenty.
No matter what it is, we'll be satisfied.

554
00:49:49,288 --> 00:49:50,736
We're not gonna get greedy.

555
00:49:53,240 --> 00:49:55,616
If we do, we'll get burned.

556
00:49:58,412 --> 00:50:00,246
You're right, darling.

557
00:50:01,415 --> 00:50:03,749
I'm sorry. I know you're right.

558
00:50:20,392 --> 00:50:23,269
I know where he is.
It's not far from here.

559
00:50:24,980 --> 00:50:28,107
- I don't want you with me.
- I thought we settled that.

560
00:50:28,275 --> 00:50:29,984
Look, I'll wait in the car...

561
00:50:30,152 --> 00:50:33,821
...but I wanna take the risk with you.
We're both doing this.

562
00:50:35,323 --> 00:50:37,908
[BOB SEGER'S "FEEL LIKE
A NUMBER" PLAYS ON STEREO]

563
00:50:39,953 --> 00:50:41,829
[MOUTHING]

564
00:51:00,974 --> 00:51:01,974
[TURNS DOWN MUSIC]

565
00:51:02,142 --> 00:51:04,769
What's the matter?
You can't think with a little music?

566
00:51:05,604 --> 00:51:08,272
It's like this, I said.
It's fast, it's hot, it's simple.

567
00:51:08,440 --> 00:51:10,191
That's it?

568
00:51:10,358 --> 00:51:13,444
Yeah, you can use the clock
or rig it to something that moves.

569
00:51:13,612 --> 00:51:16,614
It starts big.
It will go with just the mag chips.

570
00:51:16,782 --> 00:51:20,284
You want a little more,
splash a little accelerator around.

571
00:51:20,869 --> 00:51:22,495
NED:
Is it just regular gasoline?

572
00:51:22,662 --> 00:51:26,624
Yeah. Regular, unleaded, supreme.
Whatever you like, counselor.

573
00:51:28,001 --> 00:51:30,544
I got to tell you, though,
this mama's got a big drawback to her.

574
00:51:30,712 --> 00:51:33,339
- What?
- It's easy to spot.

575
00:51:33,757 --> 00:51:36,717
Even after the meltdown,
they're gonna know it's arson.

576
00:51:36,885 --> 00:51:38,177
I don't care about that.

577
00:51:38,887 --> 00:51:40,888
That's all there is to it?

578
00:51:42,349 --> 00:51:44,382
No. No, that ain't all there is to it.

579
00:51:44,383 --> 00:51:46,727
You've got to get in,
you've got to get out.

580
00:51:46,895 --> 00:51:50,898
You've got to pick the right spot,
the right time...

581
00:51:52,275 --> 00:51:55,486
...and you've gotta try not to get famous
while you're in the act.

582
00:51:55,654 --> 00:51:58,072
If that's all there was to it,
any idiot could do it.

583
00:51:58,240 --> 00:51:59,532
I'm sorry.

584
00:51:59,699 --> 00:52:01,534
Hey, now, I want to ask you something.

585
00:52:02,202 --> 00:52:04,036
Are you listening to me, asshole?

586
00:52:04,204 --> 00:52:07,540
Because I like you.
I got a serious question for you.

587
00:52:08,291 --> 00:52:09,583
What the fuck are you doing?

588
00:52:09,751 --> 00:52:11,877
This is not shit for you
to be messing with.

589
00:52:13,213 --> 00:52:17,299
You ready to hear something?
I want you to see if this sounds familiar.

590
00:52:18,009 --> 00:52:22,471
Any time you try a decent crime,
you've got 50 ways you can fuck up.

591
00:52:22,681 --> 00:52:27,685
If you think of 25 of them, then
you're a genius. And you ain't no genius.

592
00:52:28,186 --> 00:52:30,062
Remember who told me that?

593
00:52:32,440 --> 00:52:34,567
No smoking in here.

594
00:52:34,901 --> 00:52:38,946
Look, why don't you let me
do it for you? Gratis. I'll do it.

595
00:52:39,823 --> 00:52:42,074
I wouldn't be on the street
if it wasn't for you.

596
00:52:43,326 --> 00:52:44,743
Thanks.

597
00:52:45,745 --> 00:52:48,038
I sure hope you know what you're doing.

598
00:52:48,206 --> 00:52:51,417
You better be damn sure, because
if you ain't sure, then don't do it.

599
00:52:52,377 --> 00:52:54,837
Of course,
that's my recommendation anyway.

600
00:52:55,005 --> 00:52:56,380
Don't do it.

601
00:52:56,548 --> 00:53:00,926
Because I'll tell you something, counselor.
This arson is serious crime.

602
00:53:16,443 --> 00:53:17,943
NED:
And?

603
00:53:18,195 --> 00:53:21,447
MATTY: You'll be downstairs.
NED: And?

604
00:53:21,615 --> 00:53:24,450
MATTY:
Three-thirty, I send him down.

605
00:53:27,662 --> 00:53:30,664
We won't talk again
after I leave here tonight.

606
00:53:32,959 --> 00:53:36,462
I'll be in Miami by noon, Friday.
You won't be able to reach me.

607
00:53:41,134 --> 00:53:43,886
When I see you again, he'll be dead.

608
00:53:48,308 --> 00:53:50,059
I'm frightened.

609
00:55:21,443 --> 00:55:23,485
Jesus, take it easy.

610
00:55:23,653 --> 00:55:26,280
- I thought I was tense.
- Where are you going?

611
00:55:26,448 --> 00:55:28,615
I can't sleep. I'm gonna go down
and get something to drink.

612
00:55:28,783 --> 00:55:30,409
Edmund.

613
00:55:33,079 --> 00:55:35,247
I can't sleep either.

614
00:55:38,126 --> 00:55:40,252
Come back to bed, darling.

615
00:55:58,271 --> 00:56:01,398
MATTY:
No. Don't stop.

616
00:56:02,734 --> 00:56:04,443
Are you trying to kill me?

617
00:56:24,005 --> 00:56:25,297
[CREAKING]

618
00:56:26,341 --> 00:56:28,133
MATTY:
What's wrong?

619
00:56:28,885 --> 00:56:32,096
I think someone's downstairs.
I heard something.

620
00:56:32,263 --> 00:56:33,889
MATTY:
Are you sure?

621
00:56:35,683 --> 00:56:36,975
Want me to call the police?

622
00:56:37,143 --> 00:56:39,812
You be quiet.
I'm gonna nail this bastard.

623
00:56:39,979 --> 00:56:41,939
- Edmund, what's that?
- Quiet.

624
00:56:42,107 --> 00:56:45,025
- I've never seen that.
- I've got a surprise for this fucker.

625
00:57:34,200 --> 00:57:35,993
[RUSTLES]

626
00:57:52,469 --> 00:57:53,635
- He has a gun!
- Where?

627
00:57:54,345 --> 00:57:55,888
[GUNSHOT]

628
00:58:46,940 --> 00:58:49,733
NED: The car's at the end of the drive.
Clean up, then come.

629
00:58:49,901 --> 00:58:52,736
You have to be careful
driving in this fog.

630
00:58:53,696 --> 00:58:55,489
Are you all right?

631
00:58:57,325 --> 00:58:59,201
MATTY: Yeah.
- Okay.

632
00:59:35,822 --> 00:59:39,408
[HORNS HONKING]

633
01:01:00,490 --> 01:01:01,948
[SLAMS]

634
01:01:11,417 --> 01:01:13,794
MATTY: Thank God. I thought...
- Shh.

635
01:01:27,433 --> 01:01:29,685
NED: They're right on time
and I'm running late.

636
01:01:52,291 --> 01:01:54,668
We won't talk for a long time.

637
01:02:54,395 --> 01:02:57,647
[PHONE RINGS]

638
01:02:57,815 --> 01:02:59,983
BEVERLY:
Mr. Racine's office.

639
01:03:01,360 --> 01:03:03,361
Just a moment, please.

640
01:03:04,113 --> 01:03:05,197
Ned.

641
01:03:05,364 --> 01:03:07,532
Miles Hardin.
Do you want him?

642
01:03:07,700 --> 01:03:11,286
- Who is he?
- She says he's a lawyer from Miami.

643
01:03:12,079 --> 01:03:13,580
NED:
Hello.

644
01:03:13,998 --> 01:03:16,333
MAN: Mr. Racine?
- Yes?

645
01:03:16,501 --> 01:03:20,337
- Miles Hardin of Morris and Dale in Miami.
- Yes.

646
01:03:20,505 --> 01:03:24,883
As you know,
we represented Edmund Walker.

647
01:03:28,346 --> 01:03:29,763
Yes.

648
01:03:30,890 --> 01:03:32,224
Yeah.

649
01:03:32,391 --> 01:03:37,896
Well, Mrs. Walker has submitted
the new will you wrote up there.

650
01:03:41,526 --> 01:03:43,568
Uh-huh. I see.

651
01:03:44,737 --> 01:03:48,907
And frankly, Mr. Racine,
I think we may have a problem.

652
01:03:50,117 --> 01:03:51,827
Yeah, what problem is that?

653
01:03:51,994 --> 01:03:54,329
I'd rather discuss it in person.

654
01:03:54,497 --> 01:03:57,916
In fact, I think it might be best
if we could all get together up there.

655
01:03:58,084 --> 01:04:00,752
That is, if you wouldn't object.

656
01:04:01,546 --> 01:04:03,713
No. No, that would be all right.

657
01:04:03,881 --> 01:04:08,760
Good. We have a relationship with a firm
in West Palm, Shiller Hastings.

658
01:04:08,928 --> 01:04:10,804
Yes, I know them.

659
01:04:10,972 --> 01:04:13,557
I've arranged to have the use
of their offices.

660
01:04:13,724 --> 01:04:17,185
I thought we might try to make it tomorrow,
say 10:00.

661
01:04:17,353 --> 01:04:19,646
Would that be possible for you?

662
01:04:20,815 --> 01:04:22,941
- Yes, I think so.
- Good.

663
01:04:23,109 --> 01:04:26,111
Mrs. Walker told me
she'd be back up there by then...

664
01:04:26,279 --> 01:04:31,074
...and I've asked Mrs. Kraft,
Mr. Walker's sister, to join us also.

665
01:04:31,659 --> 01:04:34,160
- I'll see you then.
- Right.

666
01:04:34,328 --> 01:04:37,080
- Goodbye.
- Bye.

667
01:04:43,796 --> 01:04:45,338
I don't have her. Should I?

668
01:04:46,465 --> 01:04:50,260
I thought the temporary put her in.
She came while you were on vacation.

669
01:04:50,803 --> 01:04:53,722
Look her up.
They were in Pinehaven, I think.

670
01:04:59,854 --> 01:05:01,771
[BUZZER SOUNDS]

671
01:05:03,107 --> 01:05:04,983
BEVERLY: Get no answer
at the Pinehaven number.

672
01:05:05,693 --> 01:05:07,819
[SIGHS]

673
01:05:07,987 --> 01:05:10,071
Okay, try again later.

674
01:05:19,332 --> 01:05:22,083
- Miles Hardin, Mr. Racine.
- How are you?

675
01:05:22,251 --> 01:05:25,086
I don't think you know Mrs. Kraft.

676
01:05:26,505 --> 01:05:28,340
No, I don't.

677
01:05:29,550 --> 01:05:31,134
My condolences.

678
01:05:31,302 --> 01:05:32,844
Thank you.

679
01:05:38,476 --> 01:05:41,686
Mrs. Walker, I am very sorry
about your husband.

680
01:05:41,854 --> 01:05:43,021
Thank you, Mr. Racine.

681
01:05:43,189 --> 01:05:45,398
You know Mr. Lowenstein.

682
01:05:46,067 --> 01:05:48,068
- Hello, Peter.
- Hi.

683
01:05:53,449 --> 01:05:55,617
I've asked Mr. Lowenstein
to join us...

684
01:05:55,785 --> 01:05:59,746
...because he's handling the inquiry
into Edmund Walker's death...

685
01:05:59,914 --> 01:06:02,540
...for the county prosecutor's office.

686
01:06:02,708 --> 01:06:04,459
He and I have discussed this matter...

687
01:06:04,627 --> 01:06:07,629
...and he has made it possible
for us to speak very frankly here.

688
01:06:07,838 --> 01:06:10,382
Off the record, so to speak.

689
01:06:10,967 --> 01:06:15,136
As I've told Mrs. Walker, I was surprised
at the existence of this new will.

690
01:06:15,304 --> 01:06:18,723
Edmund hadn't mentioned
anything about it to me.

691
01:06:18,891 --> 01:06:22,644
Mrs. Walker explained that when she and
her husband decided to make changes...

692
01:06:22,812 --> 01:06:26,564
...they took care of it up here
for simplicity's sake.

693
01:06:26,732 --> 01:06:29,609
As you know, the new will
is almost identical to the old...

694
01:06:29,777 --> 01:06:32,278
...but for the disposition
of a few items.

695
01:06:32,446 --> 01:06:34,072
At the risk of oversimplifying...

696
01:06:34,240 --> 01:06:37,659
...the thrust of the will is to divide
the estate in almost equal parts...

697
01:06:37,827 --> 01:06:40,745
...between Heather Kraft
and Mrs. Walker.

698
01:06:40,913 --> 01:06:43,665
Would you agree
with that assessment, Mr. Racine?

699
01:06:45,876 --> 01:06:49,170
Yes, well, you witnessed
Edmund Walker's signature...

700
01:06:49,338 --> 01:06:53,800
...along with this
Miss Mary Ann Simpson.

701
01:06:54,260 --> 01:06:57,721
Apparently, it will be impossible for us
to contact Miss Simpson.

702
01:06:57,930 --> 01:07:00,306
MATTY:
Mary Ann is a lifelong friend of mine.

703
01:07:00,808 --> 01:07:04,519
She was visiting on her way to Europe.
When she returns, she'll be in touch.

704
01:07:04,729 --> 01:07:06,438
NED:
Although it's really not required.

705
01:07:06,605 --> 01:07:09,232
Witnesses of the signing
are not commonly available...

706
01:07:09,400 --> 01:07:12,944
...when the will is entered into probate.
It's not standard, by any means.

707
01:07:13,112 --> 01:07:16,072
HARDIN: Edmund Walker's death
was not standard.

708
01:07:16,907 --> 01:07:17,991
Pardon me, I'm confused.

709
01:07:18,159 --> 01:07:21,327
Is there some question
as to the authenticity of the will?

710
01:07:21,495 --> 01:07:22,954
I'm confused too.

711
01:07:23,122 --> 01:07:25,749
You have a problem with the witnessing
or the signatures?

712
01:07:25,916 --> 01:07:27,751
What are you getting at?

713
01:07:27,918 --> 01:07:28,960
HARDIN:
No.

714
01:07:29,295 --> 01:07:32,088
I'm afraid the problem lies elsewhere.

715
01:07:33,674 --> 01:07:36,634
Would anybody mind if I smoked?

716
01:07:49,982 --> 01:07:53,151
No, I don't need my own.
I'll just breathe the air.

717
01:08:01,452 --> 01:08:03,161
HARDIN:
Everything's in order up to there.

718
01:08:03,329 --> 01:08:06,748
The problem comes in the language
of the bequest to Heather.

719
01:08:06,916 --> 01:08:08,833
It's a technical matter.

720
01:08:09,001 --> 01:08:11,503
In writing the will,
I'm afraid Mr. Racine violated...

721
01:08:11,670 --> 01:08:14,964
...what's known as
"the rule against perpetuities."

722
01:08:15,132 --> 01:08:19,594
It forbids an inheritance to be passed
down indefinitely for generations.

723
01:08:19,762 --> 01:08:23,515
I knew that a probate judge in Miami
would spot the mistake right away...

724
01:08:24,100 --> 01:08:27,018
...so I thought I'd bring it up here
to Okeelanta County...

725
01:08:27,186 --> 01:08:29,062
...since Edmund
had the residence here...

726
01:08:29,230 --> 01:08:31,322
...and see if I could get lucky
with a judge...

727
01:08:31,323 --> 01:08:33,274
...who didn't know estate law
quite so well.

728
01:08:33,442 --> 01:08:37,237
Perhaps find one with the same
